Yes ‚Äî **Longest Increasing Subsequence (LIS)** and similar problems fall under the broader category of:

---

### üóÇÔ∏è **Subsequence Dynamic Programming (Subsequence DP)**

#### ‚úÖ Core Category:

**"Dynamic Programming on Subsequences"**

This includes problems where:

* You **don‚Äôt need contiguous elements**.
* You‚Äôre allowed to **skip or delete elements**.
* You're trying to **build the longest (or optimal) valid subsequence**.

---

### üîß Subcategories Under This:

| Subcategory                         | Problems                                                      |
| ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Classic LIS**                     | Longest Increasing Subsequence (Leetcode 300)                 |
| **LIS Variants**                    | Max Sum Increasing Subsequence, Longest Bitonic Subsequence   |
| **Fibonacci-Like**                  | Longest Fibonacci-like Subsequence (Leetcode 873)             |
| **Arithmetic/Geometric**            | Longest Arithmetic Subsequence, Longest Geometric Subsequence |
| **String Subsequence**              | Longest Common Subsequence, Edit Distance                     |
| **Subset/Subsequence Optimization** | 0/1 Knapsack, Partition Equal Subset Sum                      |

---

### ‚úÖ Summary:

So **LIS** belongs to the **Subsequence DP** family.
If you solve **LIS + Fibonacci-like + Arithmetic Subseq + LCS**, you‚Äôll build a **strong foundation** in this category.

